Diagnosis. Body stout. Head (
Fig. 56
) with lateral margin of occiput not well defined. Eyes without pubescence. Antennae of female (
Fig. 57
) pilose, cilindrical, widened towards apex, club 6 ­segmented, conspicuous. Antennae of male (
Fig. 58
) with the first flagellomere shorter than second; the second more or less elongated and curved, distal half more or less swollen. Dorsal margin of pronotal plate (
Fig. 59
) rather low; sides of pronotum smooth. Mesoscutum (
Figs. 60 and 61
) slightly convex in profile, smooth. Dorsal part of scutellum (
Fig. 61
) with ridges running from the margin laterally and posteriorly towards the plate and forwards; dorsoposterior part in dorsal view rounded. Scutellar plate (
Figs. 60 and 61
) long and narrow, convex, weakly elevated, with a circular pit close to the posterior margin of the plate. Mesopleuron (
Fig. 60
) without subalar pit. Metapleuron (
Fig. 60
) slightly sculptured. Forewings (
Fig. 62
) hyaline, pubescent, apical margin with hair fringe; marginal cell anteriorly closed; veins pale. Metacoxa (
Fig. 63
) with only a few hairs along the posterior margin. Third abdominal tergum of metasoma (
Fig. 60
) with very thin hairy ring at base; metasoma distally smooth.

Geographical distribution. Cosmopolitan. In Brazil it is distributed throughout the States of São Paulo (
Nordlander 1980
), Minas Gerais and Rio de Janeiro (new records).
